tokio-rs/tokio#6053.body:
Current phrasing in [tutorial](https://tokio.rs/tokio/tutorial/channels):

> When every Sender has gone out of scope or has otherwise been dropped, it is no longer possible to send more messages into the channel. At this point, the recv call on the Receiver will return None, which means that all senders are gone and the channel is closed.

The second statement is blatantly wrong because `recv` can still receive messages sent before senders drop.

```rust
use std::time::Duration;
use tokio::sync::mpsc;
use tokio::time::sleep;

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    let (tx, mut rx) = mpsc::channel(32);
    let tx2 = tx.clone();

    tokio::spawn(async move {
        tx.send("sending from first handle").await.unwrap();
        drop(tx);
        println!("tx droppped");
    });

    tokio::spawn(async move {
        tx2.send("sending from second handle").await.unwrap();
        drop(tx2);
        println!("tx2 droppped");
    });

    sleep(Duration::from_secs(2)).await;

    while let Some(message) = rx.recv().await {
        println!("GOT = {}", message);
    }
}
```

In [docs](https://docs.rs/tokio/latest/tokio/sync/mpsc/index.html#disconnection):

> When all [Sender](https://docs.rs/tokio/latest/tokio/sync/mpsc/struct.Sender.html) handles have been dropped, it is no longer possible to send values into the channel. This is considered the termination event of the stream. As such, Receiver::poll returns Ok(Ready(None)).

This looks more correct but I have never tested with `Receiver::poll`.

tokio-rs/tokio#7990.body:
**Version**
1.50.0 / `master` at `a8435c0`

**Platform**
`Linux antigravity 6.19.7-1-default #1 SMP PREEMPT_DYNAMIC Thu Mar 12 11:27:25 UTC 2026 (7f7ff04) x86_64 x86_64 x86_64 GNU/Linux`

**Description**

As [described in `#tokio-internals`](https://discord.com/channels/500028886025895936/1479686902339735583), `tokio::mpsc::Chan::recv_many` makes incorrect assumptions about the provided buffer when exiting through the post-loop `rx_fields.rx_closed && self.inner.semaphore.is_idle()` code path.

`assert!(buffer.is_empty());` asserts the incorrect precondition, it should `assert_eq!(buffer.len(), initial_length);` instead.

The following tests trigger the faulty assertion for bounded and unbounded channels:

```rust
#[should_panic]
#[maybe_tokio_test]
async fn recv_many_with_non_empty_buffer_bounded_rx_closed_and_idle() {
    let (_tx, mut rx) = mpsc::channel::<i32>(1);

    let mut buffer: Vec<i32> = vec![1];

    rx.close();

    // Panics, incorrectly expecting an empty buffer.
    rx.recv_many(&mut buffer, 1).await;
}

#[should_panic]
#[maybe_tokio_test]
async fn recv_many_with_non_empty_buffer_unbounded_rx_closed_and_idle() {
    let (_tx, mut rx) = mpsc::unbounded_channel::<i32>();

    let mut buffer: Vec<i32> = vec![1];

    rx.close();

    // Panics, incorrectly expecting an empty buffer.
    rx.recv_many(&mut buffer, 1).await;
}
```

I will provide a PR.
